Intel Changes
-------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-09-17/intel-l=
ands-amazon-chip-deal-amid-foundry-split-plant-pullback ) :

Intel Corp. shares surged for the second straight day after the troubled ch=
ipmaker made a raft of announcements, spurring optimism that a turnaround p=
lan is starting to bear fruit. In the most notable move, the company struck=
 a multibillion-dollar deal with Amazon.com Inc.=E2=80=99s Amazon Web Servi=
ces cloud unit to coinvest in a custom AI semiconductor. Intel also may rec=
eive as much as $3 billion in US government funding to make chips for the m=
ilitary. And it=E2=80=99s turning its ailing manufacturing business, or fou=
ndry, into a wholly owned subsidiary. But the chipmaker is pulling back in =
some areas as well. Intel said it would shelve plans for new factories in G=
ermany and Poland =E2=80=94 at least for now.

The news follows a meeting of Intel=E2=80=99s board last week, during which=
 executives presented ways to conserve cash while keeping Chief Executive O=
fficer Pat Gelsinger=E2=80=99s longer-term turnaround plan on track. The CE=
O=E2=80=99s effort hinges on transforming Intel into a foundry, but the San=
ta Clara, California-based company has been slow to line up customers. A hi=
gh-profile client such as Amazon represents a significant win.

The Amazon news is certainly notable, it=E2=80=99s not clear how big of a d=
eal it is yet; from the Intel press release ( https://www.intel.com/content=
/www/us/en/newsroom/news/intel-strategic-collaboration.html#gs.f1745d ) :

Intel Corp. and Amazon Web Services. Inc., an Amazon.com company, today ann=
ounced a co-investment in custom chip designs under a multi-year, multi-bil=
lion-dollar framework covering product and wafers from Intel. This is a sig=
nificant expansion of the two companies=E2=80=99 longstanding strategic col=
laboration to help customers power virtually any workload and accelerate th=
e performance of artificial intelligence (AI) applications.

As part of the expanded collaboration, Intel will produce an AI fabric chip=
 for AWS on Intel 18A, the company=E2=80=99s most advanced process node. In=
tel will also produce a custom Xeon 6 chip on Intel 3, building on the exis=
ting partnership under which Intel produces Xeon Scalable processors for AW=
S.

I suspect that most of the dollars in this deal have to do with that last s=
entence, i.e. custom Xeon chips for AWS. As the press release notes, this i=
sn=E2=80=99t a new program, nor is the idea of expanding the degree of cust=
omizability available to Xeon customers new news. This has always been a pa=
rt of the foundry plan.

The AI fabric chip is more interesting, but in part because of what it is n=
ot: specifically, this is not about manufacturing AWS=E2=80=99s Trainium or=
 Inferentia AI-focused chips, much less the company=E2=80=99s ARM-based Gra=
viton chips; all of those are being manufactured by TSMC. Notably, all of t=
hose chips are manufactured on somewhat trailing edge processes: Graviton3 =
is on TSMC=E2=80=99s 5nm process, and Trainium2 and Inferentia2 are on TSMC=
=E2=80=99s 7nm process.

That speaks to the long-term potential of this deal for both Amazon and Int=
el. Amazon would surely like to be on a leading-edge process, but at TSMC i=
t has to wait in line behind Apple (already on 3nm for two generations), Qu=
alcomm (launching its first 3nm chip this year), Intel (who just launched 3=
nm chips), AMD (launching 3nm chips this year), Nvidia (currently on 4nm), =
MediaTek (currently on 4nm), and Broadcom (currently on 5nm; Google TPUs ar=
e on 7nm). If Intel can pull off 18A and 14A then AWS is positioning itself=
 to be at the head of the line; by extension, the upside of Intel=E2=80=99s=
 fab efforts is in providing a legitimate alternative for the fastest proce=
sses.

That, though, is in the future: the only chip that AWS is signing up for, o=
utside of Xeons, is a new AI fabric chip. =E2=80=9CFabric chip=E2=80=9D is =
a fairly imprecise term; I=E2=80=99m interpreting it as referring to an int=
erconnect chip that links together multiple parts of a system to allow for =
greater scalability. AWS obviously has the need for such a chip as it seeks=
 to scale out its own AI chips; it=E2=80=99s also something that is new to =
the company (which perhaps makes it easier to start at a new supplier), and=
 also not currently mission critical. To put it another way, it=E2=80=99s a=
 good =E2=80=9Cprove it or lose it=E2=80=9D product for Intel, which is to =
say this is good news, but not yet a fab savior.

Meanwhile, both the deal for military chips and the delay in new European f=
abs are expected yet welcome all the same; it=E2=80=99s past time for the U=
.S. to actually start delivering some of the funding from the CHIPS act, an=
d at the same time, Intel needs to consolidate its efforts and conserve its=
 cash. If Europe wants more investment its going to have to pony up a lot m=
ore money and deliver it directly.

That leaves the final bit: Intel Foundry will become its own subsidiary, no=
t just its own division. This is an obvious move that mostly mystifies me i=
n terms of why Intel didn=E2=80=99t just jump to this end state immediately=
. A subsidiary much more strongly formalizes the separation Intel needs to =
deliver a guarantee to customers in terms of the separation between its fab=
s and design units; it also gets the unit in a state to be invested in dire=
ctly or to be spun off =E2=80=94 or sold.

Qualcomm-Intel Rumors
---------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/business/deals/qualcomm-=
approached-intel-about-a-takeover-in-recent-days-fa114f9d ) :

Chip giant Qualcomm made a takeover approach to rival Intel in recent days,=
 according to people familiar with the matter, in what would be one of the =
largest and most consequential deals in recent years. A deal for Intel, whi=
ch has a market value of roughly $90 billion, would come as the chip maker =
has been suffering through one of the most significant crises in its five-d=
ecade history.

A deal is far from certain, the people cautioned. Even if Intel is receptiv=
e, a deal of that size is all but certain to attract antitrust scrutiny, th=
ough it is also possible it could be seen as an opportunity to strengthen t=
he U.S.=E2=80=99s competitive edge in chips. To get the deal done, Qualcomm=
 could intend to sell assets or parts of Intel to other buyers.

It=E2=80=99s probably best to start out with an explanation as to why a dea=
l like this is pretty unlikely. First and foremost, it=E2=80=99s not clear =
how Qualcomm would pay for it: the company has $13 billion on hand, and fre=
e cash flows of around $10 billion; the problem is that a leveraged buy-out=
 is complicated by the fact that Intel has negative cash flows (-$4.2 billi=
on in the first six months of this year) as it seeks to build out its fab b=
usiness.

Or course Qualcomm might just want the chip business, which produced $2.9 b=
illion of profit last quarter; there actually isn=E2=80=99t that much overl=
ap (with the exception of MobilEye, which could be easily spun out; interes=
tingly, it would help Qualcomm that Apple already acquired Intel=E2=80=99s =
modem business), and given that x86 is likely to remain the dominant 3rd-pa=
rty solution for data centers (i.e. most ARM server chips will be developed=
 in-house) and Windows PCs, this significantly expands Qualcomm=E2=80=99s m=
arket in terms of chips. Intel also has a lot of IP that Qualcomm is, needl=
ess to say, very good at exploiting.

That, though, gets at two big blockers. First, Intel and AMD have an in-dep=
th cross-licensing deal that is downstream from AMD developing the architec=
ture for 64-bit processing; as I understand it that deal goes away if a cha=
nge in control happens at either company, which is to say that a Qualcomm-o=
wned Intel couldn=E2=80=99t actually ship any chips without making a new de=
al with AMD, which is in a much stronger negotiating position these days. S=
econdly, while the legitimate antitrust concerns are surprisingly minimal, =
that didn=E2=80=99t stop China from blocking Intel=E2=80=99s Tower acquisit=
ion, likely as retaliation for the chip ban. Given that the number one reas=
on to let this deal happen is to save Intel as a U.S. champion, that is a b=
ig concern.

All of that is a roundabout way to say that this is a deal that is compelli=
ng in a vacuum, at least from a U.S. and Intel perspective. The most import=
ant part of Intel from a national security perspective =E2=80=94 and, in th=
e very long run, the part of the company with the largest upside =E2=80=94 =
is Intel Foundry; the most valuable part of Intel in the short-term, though=
, is Intel=E2=80=99s chip design business. There is definitely a real elega=
nce in terms of selling the latter to get the former off the ground, partic=
ularly since Intel Foundry will in the very long run be better off on its o=
wn; in terms of the short to medium run, though, what is equally compelling=
 is linking the deal to not just guarantees that Intel chips be fabbed at I=
ntel Foundry, but Qualcomm chips as well. That is the sort of foundational =
customer Intel Foundry needs.

Ultimately, though, it=E2=80=99s harder to see the allure for Qualcomm in t=
his sort of deal; maybe that is why Reuters reported ( https://www.reuters.=
com/markets/deals/qualcomm-approached-intel-about-takeover-recent-days-wsj-=
reports-2024-09-20/ ) that the Wall Street Journal=E2=80=99s report was act=
ually about the expansion of Qualcomm interest from just the chip-making pa=
rts to the whole company, perhaps structured as a merger as opposed to an a=
cquisition. You can definitely make the case that the biggest upside for Qu=
alcomm=E2=80=99s free cash flow is funding Intel Foundry, the fortunes of w=
hich would be significantly enhanced by adding Qualcomm=E2=80=99s chip busi=
ness as a customer. That, though, elides the real challenges that would be =
entailed in such a large scale merger, particularly since Qualcomm (unlike,=
 say, Broadcom), isn=E2=80=99t exactly renowned for cutting effectively or =
spending money efficiently, and isn=E2=80=99t exactly a beloved partner for=
 other companies in the industry.

All that said, if this happened I would support it, and I think that folks =
shouldn=E2=80=99t be so quick to dismiss creative solutions to Intel=E2=80=
=99s immediate needs for cash and customers; my biggest concern, frankly, i=
s China. One wonders what would happen if both parties were to decide they =
just didn=E2=80=99t care.

Microsoft and Three Mile Island
-------------------------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-09-20/microso=
ft-s-ai-power-needs-prompt-revival-of-three-mile-island-nuclear-plant ) :

The owner of the shuttered Three Mile Island nuclear plant in Pennsylvania =
will invest $1.6 billion to revive it, agreeing to sell all the output to M=
icrosoft Corp. as the tech titan seeks carbon-free electricity for data cen=
ters to power the artificial intelligence boom.

Constellation Energy Corp., the biggest US operator of reactors, expects Th=
ree Mile Island to go back into service in 2028, according to a statement F=
riday. While one of the site=E2=80=99s two units permanently closed almost =
a half-century ago after the worst US nuclear accident, Constellation is pl=
anning to reopen the other reactor, which shut in 2019 because it couldn=E2=
=80=99t compete economically.

A few quick takeaways:

* First, nuclear energy and data centers are a perfect match for two reason=
s. The most obvious one is that data centers need power 24/7, which nuclear=
 provides. The less obvious one is that nuclear power needs to be deliverin=
g power 24/7; it doesn=E2=80=99t scale down. Data centers, though, are a pe=
rfectly predictable consumer of power.
* The ideal nuclear power plant would be co-located with a data center to a=
void any power loss from transmission; unfortunately in this case Three Mil=
e Island would be used to power multiple data centers across several states=
. In fact, the biggest hold-up in bringing things back on line may be acqui=
ring interconnect.
* It=E2=80=99s interesting that Microsoft (and a similar investment from Am=
azon ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-03-28/amazon-bets-150-b=
illion-on-data-centers-required-for-ai-boom ) ) is motivated by their commi=
tment to run on clean energy; I certainly welcome them following through on=
 that commitment, which, to be honest, I thought they would just silently a=
bandon in the face of AI-driven demand growth.

To that end, the biggest takeaway is that this is pretty compelling evidenc=
e about just how confident Microsoft is in AI and long-run demand. Yes, Azu=
re is a big business with big power needs regardless, but deals of this siz=
e weren=E2=80=99t really in the picture before AI came along. One certainly=
 hopes for more, and perhaps in the process, a bending in the price curve f=
or not just restarting nuclear plants, but building new ones. That, though,=
 still seems unlikely, even though the aforementioned benefits in terms of =
baseline capacity really do make sense for data centers in particular.

